              }
              \end{tikzpicture}
              \hfill <m>\cdots</m>
              <solution permid="GVW">
                First, we find the number of vertices in the <m>n</m> th figure to be <m>v_n = 3n^2 +3n + 1</m> (you can use polynomial fitting, or notice that every time you add a larger multiple of 6 and use triangular numbers).

                Of these vertices, there will be 6 with degree 2 (the corners), <m>6n-6</m> with degree 4 (the sides) and the rest, <m>3n^2 - 3n</m> with degree 6.  Adding up the degrees and dividing by 2 gives the number of edges: <m>e_n = 9n^2 + 3n</m>.

                Finally, we can use Euler's formula to find the number of triangles.  However, since we don't want to count the outside, we would have
                <me permid="nze">
                  f_n = 1 + 9n^2 + 3n - (3n^2 + 3n + 1) = 6n^2
                </me>.
