          <exercise permid="vdd">
            <statement>
              <p permid="Boo">
                Consider the statement, <q>For all sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
                if <m>|A| = |B|</m> then <m>|A \cup B| = 2|A|</m>.</q>

                <ol permid="QEd">
                  <li permid="XNd">
                    <p permid="lof">
                      Write the converse and the contrapositive of the statement.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li permid="DUm">
                    <p permid="Rvo">
                      Is the original statement true?
                      Explain.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li permid="kbv">
                    <p permid="xCx">
                      Is the converse of the original statement true?
                      Explain.
                    </p>
                  </li>

                  <li permid="QiE">
                    <p permid="dJG">
                      Consider another statement: <q>For
                      <m>A = \{1,2\}</m> and <m>B = \{1\}</m>,
                      if <m>|A| = |B|</m> then <m>|A \cup B| = 2|A|</m>.</q>
                      Explain why this statement is true,
                      but that does not tell us anything about the truth of the original statement or its converse.
                    </p>
                  </li>
                </ol>
              </p>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution permid="zrx">
            <p permid="TNr">
              <ol permid="jNa">
                <li permid="wpN">
                  <p permid="JQP">
                    The converse: For all sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
                    if <m>|A \cup B| = 2|A|</m>, then <m>|A| = |B|</m>.

                    The contrapositive: For all sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>,
                    if <m>|A \cup B| \ne 2|A|</m> then <m>|A| \ne |B|</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li permid="cwW">
                  <p permid="pXY">
                    The original statement is false.
                    That means that there <em>exists</em>
                    sets <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> such that
                    <m>|A| = |B|</m> but <m>|A \cup B| \ne 2|A|</m>.
                    We can prove this by giving an example of such sets:
                    <m>A = \{1,2\}</m> and <m>B= \{2,3\}</m>.
                    These sets have the same cardinality,
                    but <m>A \cup B = \{1,2,3\}</m> has cardinality 3, not 4.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li permid="IEf">
                  <p permid="Wfh">
                    The converse is false as well.
                    Take <m>A = \{1,2\}</m> and <m>B = \{2,3,4\}</m>.
                    Now we have <m>|A \cup B| = 4 = 2|A|</m> but <m>|A| = 2</m> and <m>|B| = 3</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li permid="oLo">
                  <p permid="Cmq">
                    The new statement is about specific sets.
                    For these sets, <m>|A| \ne |B|</m>,
                    so the hypothesis of the implication is false.
                    That makes the entire statement true automatically
                    (even though the conclusion is false).
                    This one example does not prove that the original implication is true
                    (after all, it is not).
                    It also cannot prove that the original statement is false,
                    as it is not a counterexample.
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
            </p>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

      <exercise permid="bkm">
        <statement>
          <p permid="hvx">
            Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be sets with <m>|A| = 9</m> and <m>|B| = 16</m>,
            and <m>|A \cup B| = 25</m>.
            Find <m>A \cap B</m>.
