      <exercise permid="qtk">
        <statement>
          <p permid="oEx">
            Prove, using strong induction,
            that every positive integer can be written as the sum of distinct powers of 2.
            For example, <m>13 = 1 + 4 + 8 = 2^0 + 2^2 + 2^3</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution permid="GAx">
          <p permid="aWr">
            Note that <m>1 = 2^0</m> -- this is your base case.
            Now suppose <m>k</m> can be written as the sum of distinct powers of 2 for all <m>1\le k \le n</m>.
            We can then write <m>n</m> as the sum of distinct powers of 2 as follows:
            subtract the largest power of 2 less than <m>n</m> from <m>n</m>.
            That is, write <m>n = 2^j + k</m> for the largest possible <m>j</m>.
            But <m>k</m> is now less than <m>n</m>,
            and also less than <m>2^j</m>,
            so write <m>k</m> as the sum of distinct powers of 2
            (we can do so by the inductive hypothesis).
            Thus <m>n</m> can be written as the sum of distinct powers of 2 for all <m>n \ge 1</m>.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>

